author: @threeMetreJim
text: How about trying a network that controls the parameters of a source - filter model (synthesiser) of speech (an LPC coder??). You don't need many parameters. Train to generate a spectrogram that matches the transcription as closely as possible. Training doesn't require audio samples, but the spectrograms for them. Inputs are time, letter at time (yes just 2 inputs)., outputs are the parameters for the synthesiser. Training data split into sentences to capture the timing and pitch change.

author: @sc0tty319
text: Leaving this comment for ppl who actually want to try on regular pc. You will get a sense of if your gig would work or not.  I have GeForce GTX 1060 3GB and 8 GB of memory RAM. I ran into memory problem. So I reduced the batch even to size 1.  But still ran out of memory. I believe sentdex has high standard what he meant a regular gaming pc. Sentdex's local machine is better than 2080ti  with lots of rams. Here's my summary of the failed journey... [1.] made little changes to the code so it would run on my 2015 macbook pro(no nvidia GPU) using just cpu, but it would take forever to train. [2.] Tried on Windows (nvidia GPU), but found out PC and the code is not compatible. Tensorflow version that works with the code is not supported on PC. [3.] Installed Ubuntu and all necessaries (https://medium.com/@aspiring1/installing-cuda-toolkit-10-0-and-cudnn-for-deep-learning-with-tensorflow-gpu-on-ubuntu-18-04-lts-f7e968b24c98). [4.] GPU would show up in nvidia-smi, but could not load it to tensorflow. Used Anaconda instead of Pip to install tensorflow-gpu. Worked. [5.] Found out my gig have memory problem. Reduced batch size to 1. [6.] Failed. But it was fun. [7.] Calculated how the cost of renting a Cloud deep learning machine. Too expensive. Planning to build a local deep learning machine once I have the money. About 3 months of regular usage of the machine would break-even.

author: @threeMetreJim
text: I wonder if it might be better to do speech to speech, i.e an impersonator.  You might then be able to use a not very good text to speech and have it 'corrected' by the neural network.  Would be a lot better for faking a phone call too, no need to type your reply if you could feed it with your own voice - wouldn't be able to listen to it at the same time though, if it's changing the intonation and pitch (you'd need a speech to text so you could see what was being said), it's bad enough trying that with a 'dumb' voice changer. I still think the source - filter model is probably the best way to generate high fidelity speech; less data throughput and more processing power nowadays for many more parameters and could easily be controlled by a neural network - might be a good for using a GAN on too.

author: @finnmccool8671
text: I wonder how much musical interpretation could be used in this. It was interesting that the voices sounded 'autotuned'. They also sounded 'quantised'. By that I mean that every instrument recorded on songs from 2000 onwards is lined up to a 16th note. It makes it easier to shuffle sounds about and you only need one small sample. Autotune tries to match  every note the singer makes to a scale note in the key of the song if it is slightly off. Adam Levine?  The BPM remains constant over the whole song and the sound is compressed to feck. An old music teacher told me that the most important parts of music are the silences between notes. Your voice simulations sound pretty good. The nuances , silences, changes in timbre and inflection are what is missing. Perhaps the machine learning is concentrating on the wrong part of vocalisation. Then again. I could just be talking shi*e. :-)

text: VERY interested in seeing a tutorial about this. I'm doing research in the area of fake content as part of a community engagement activism movement so being able to generate better "fake" or manipulated voices is pretty important. I've been putting off working on the audio part of it as the video is still a work in progress, so I'd really appreciate seeing some more information on exactly the steps you are taking. I like the idea of transfer learning off of some basic stereotypes. Maybe train on a few audiobooks with transcriptions for the basic voices?   Anyway, interesting work and really appreciate the sharing! exciting times! and scary too (I agree with your comment about people not being aware, which is why I'm trying to raise it as part of the activism effort).

author: @DickyBenfield
text: I have transcribed audio manually, but I was doing kind of what like the speech to text systems would do and leave out fillers. Beyond that and in a different vein but still related, I have also gone in by hand and created new phonetic rules for words to get the text to speech pronounce things closer to correct. It has gotten SOOOOOOO much better in recent years... I remember when I would buy voices that had accents because the accents would just generally sound less synthetic and fake than American English voices. lol... Now it is getting to the point that I could have books read by whomever I wanted!!! I suddenly want to hear some synthesized speech as Morgan Freeman and other iconic voices... I wonder how confused it would get training on people that do a lot of impressions and a log of different voices in their performances, like Jim Carrey or Kevin Spacey?
